  "prompt": "America is divided into how many classes of people?",
  "response": "In the United States, people are often categorized into social classes based on various factors such as income, education, occupation, and wealth. While there is no official classification, a commonly used framework divides Americans into several broad classes:\n\n1. **Upper Class**: This group includes individuals and families with significant wealth, high income, and substantial assets. They often have considerable influence and access to resources.\n\n2. **Upper Middle Class**: Composed of well-educated professionals and managers with higher incomes. They typically hold advanced degrees and have a comfortable lifestyle.\n\n3. **Middle Class**: This includes individuals and families with moderate income levels who often work in professional, managerial, or skilled jobs. They may own homes and prioritize education and savings.\n\n4. **Working Class**: Often consisting of individuals and families with lower income levels who work in manual or service jobs. They may have less job security and fewer benefits.\n\n5. **Lower Class**: This group includes individuals with the lowest income levels, often facing economic instability and limited access to education and healthcare. They may rely on government assistance.\n\nThese categories are not rigid and can vary by region, and individual circumstances. Additionally, there is ongoing debate about the definitions and boundaries of these classes, as well as the factors that contribute to social mobility in America.",
